  <h1>Google Business Profile for architects</h1>
  <p class="lede">
    About 18,100 times a month, someone types "architect near me" and Google
    answers with a map and three names. That shortlist is assembled by an
    algorithm, costs nothing to enter, and most firms have never once opened
    the profile that decides whether they are on it.
  </p>

  <p>
    We build paid pipelines for architecture firms, so a free channel is an odd thing for us to open with. This one earns it. The map sits above the rankings your <a href="/seo-for-architects">SEO for architects</a> work is grinding toward, entry is a profile that takes an afternoon, and most of your competitors have abandoned theirs.
  </p>

  <div class="answer">
    <p class="answer-label">The short answer</p>
    <p>To get an architecture firm into Google's map pack: claim the profile, pick the most specific category, fill every field, load real project photos, and collect reviews on a schedule, asked for at each project's happiest week. Profile signals and reviews together drive roughly half the local ranking. Residential firms get leads straight off the map. Commercial firms get their due-diligence check passed, which is quieter and worth just as much.</p>
  </div>

  <h2>The shortlist Google runs without you</h2>
  <p>
    Search anything with local intent, "architect near me" or "residential
    architect" plus your city, and Google plants a map near the top of the page
    with three businesses under it. The local pack. Those three get the profile
    visits, the calls, and the quiet authority of looking like the answer.
    Position four might as well be page nine.
  </p>
  <p>
    Now the uncomfortable part. Google builds a profile for your firm whether
    you participate or not, assembled from whatever the internet happens to say
    about you. Unclaimed, that can mean a map pin pointing at the dry cleaner
    next door, hours you have never kept, and one photo of your office door
    from 2019. Buyers assume you chose all of it.
  </p>

  <h2>"But Maps is for plumbers"</h2>
  <p>
    That is the standard objection, and the numbers disagree. "Architect near
    me" pulls about 18,100 US searches a month, with "architects near me" and
    "architecture firms near me" adding roughly 12,100 each. The same click
    costs around nine dollars when you buy it as an ad. The map hands it to
    you free.
  </p>
  <p>
    If you do <strong>residential</strong> work, the map is a direct lead source. A homeowner types "architect near me" late in the journey, usually with land bought and a builder already in their ear, which makes them one of the most qualified strangers who will ever go looking for you. Three firms get shown. Everyone else is, functionally, closed.
  </p>
  <p>
    If you do <strong>commercial</strong> work, developers do not pick architects off a map, and it would worry us if they did. Your profile works a different shift: due diligence. Search your firm's name and the profile takes over the right side of the screen. BrightLocal's 2025 survey found 88 percent of consumers use Google to find reviews of local businesses, and a developer vetting a shortlist behaves the same way, just with a bigger spreadsheet.
  </p>
  <p>
    It is the same Google check that quietly filters your referrals, the one we covered in <a href="/referral-systems-for-architects">referral systems for architects</a>: your name comes up at dinner, and before dessert someone has searched it. The profile is what they find. Empty is an answer too. And whatever the profile promises, the click lands on your website next, where <a href="/website-design-for-architects">website design for architects</a> decides whether the visit survives.
  </p>

  <h2>What decides who makes the pack</h2>
  <p>
    Google names three factors: relevance, distance, and prominence. In
    Whitespark's 2026 survey of local search experts, profile signals carry 32
    percent of the local pack decision and reviews another 20 percent. Half the
    game lives inside a profile most firms opened once, at gunpoint, in 2021.
    And the parts you control are not mysterious.
  </p>

  <h3>1. Pick the category like money depends on it</h3>
  <p>
    Your primary category is one of the heaviest signals you get to choose.
    Pick the most specific one Google offers for what you actually sell, not
    the vaguest one that felt safe. Then make the rest of the profile agree
    with it: the services list, the description, the service area. Write them
    for a buyer, not a search engine. Keyword stuffing reads as desperate to
    both.
  </p>

  <h3>2. Fill in every field Google gives you</h3>
  <p>
    Google's own guidance says complete profiles are more likely to show up in
    local results, which is about as close as Google gets to handing out an
    answer key. Address or service area, hours, description, services, real
    contact details. It is unglamorous data entry, it takes one afternoon, and
    it is the cheapest ranking work you will ever do.
  </p>

  <h3>3. Run reviews on a schedule, not on luck</h3>
  <p>
    Reviews are a fifth of the ranking and most of the persuasion, and they
    respond to systems. Ask at the peak: move-in week for residential clients,
    opening day or the first occupancy numbers for commercial ones. Then answer
    every review you get. Only 42 percent of people now trust reviews as much
    as a personal recommendation, down from 79 in 2020, so buyers read them
    skeptically, and a considered owner reply is the part that reads as real.
  </p>

  <h3>4. Post photos of finished work</h3>
  <p>
    You sell the way buildings look, and the default photos on an unclaimed
    profile are whatever Street View saw that day. Load finished projects and
    keep loading them as work completes, because a profile that visibly moves
    reads as a firm that is busy. No stock, no renders passed off as builds.
    Buyers can tell.
  </p>

  <h3>5. Do not get clever with addresses</h3>
  <p>
    A fake office to enter a second city's pack is the local version of buying
    backlinks: it works until Google notices, then the whole profile gets
    suspended while your real leads bounce. If you work from home, set the
    profile up as a service-area business and hide the address. Eligible,
    honest, and it keeps your living room off the internet.
  </p>

  <h2>Where the map stops working</h2>
  <p>
    The pack rewards proximity, not portfolio. Distance is one of Google's
    three factors, and no amount of optimizing moves your office. You compete
    inside a radius Google decides, for whoever happens to search this week,
    ranked by an algorithm that offers you no dials. You cannot show up to more
    buyers than exist, and you cannot choose which ones.
  </p>
  <p>
    That is the gap between capturing demand and creating it. The profile catches people already looking for an architect nearby. It does nothing about the buyers who have not started searching, homeowners quietly planning a build if you do residential, developers and business owners with a project taking shape if you do commercial. Reaching them first, at a volume you control, is the job of paid ads, and the full case is in <a href="/meta-ads-for-architects">Meta ads for architects</a>.
  </p>
  <p>
    So run both, with expectations in the right order: the profile is free capture, set up once and maintained lightly, and the paid engine is where growth actually gets decided. How the two slot into one system is mapped in <a href="/architecture-marketing">architecture marketing</a> and built out in <a href="/lead-generation-for-architects">lead generation for architects</a>.
  </p>

  <h2>A few honest answers</h2>
  <h3>Can you pay Google for a better local ranking?</h3>
  <p>
    Not the organic pack. Google's words: "There's no way to request or pay for a better local ranking on Google." What money can buy is the sponsored slot that sometimes sits above the map, which is a different game with different math, covered in <a href="/google-ads-for-architects">Google Ads for architects</a>.
  </p>
  <h3>How many reviews do I need?</h3>
  <p>
    More than the three firms Google currently shows instead of you, and
    fresher. There is no magic number. A steady trickle beats a pile from 2022,
    because recency is part of what Google and buyers both read. Two reviews a
    quarter, asked for at the happiest moment of each project, can quietly pass
    firms twice your age.
  </p>
  <h3>I do commercial work across three metros. Does any of this matter?</h3>
  <p>
    The pack matters least for you. The profile still matters. You will not
    map-pack in a city where you have no real address, and faking one gets the
    profile suspended. But every developer who hears your name runs the brand
    search, and a profile with reviews from past clients is what answers it.
    Treat it as your due diligence page, not your lead source, and let the
    outbound engine do the traveling. Press coverage works the same shift, which is <a href="/pr-and-press-for-architects">PR and press for architects</a>.
  </p>

  <h2>Claim the map this week</h2>
  <p>
    An afternoon of setup, a photo habit, a review ask built into project
    closeout, and you are ahead of most firms in your metro on a channel that
    costs nothing but attention. Then build the part no map gives you: demand
    you can turn up on purpose, from buyers who were never going to search.
    Building that engine for architecture firms is what we do all day.
  </p>
